Class LinkedListOfStrings

java.lang.Object
problem2.LinkedListOfStrings
All Implemented Interfaces:
IListOfStrings
public class LinkedListOfStrings extends Object implements IListOfStrings
A singly-linked list implementation of the IListOfStrings ADT.

Internally, the list is maintained as a chain of Node objects. The head points to the first element; the tail node's next is null. An empty list is represented by a null head.

All mutating operations (addFront(String)) modify the list in-place, while read-only operations that return a new list (filterLargerThan(int), removeDuplicates()) never modify the receiver and always return a fresh LinkedListOfStrings.

Complexity notes:
  • isEmpty, size — O(n) for size (no cached counter)
  • contains, containsAll — O(n) and O(n·m)
  • filterLargerThan, removeDuplicates — O(n²) worst case
  • hasDuplicates — O(n²) worst case

    • containsAll

      public boolean containsAll(IListOfStrings other)
      Checks whether every element of the given list is also present in this list.

      Returns true vacuously if other is empty, because every element of an empty set is trivially contained in any set.

      For each element in other, calls contains(String) on this. Runs in O(n·m) time where n = this.size(), m = other.size().

      Specified by:
      containsAll in interface IListOfStrings
      Parameters:
      other - the list of strings to check for; must not be null
      Returns:
      true if all elements of other are in this list; false otherwise
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - if other is null

    • filterLargerThan

      public IListOfStrings filterLargerThan(int maxLength)
      Returns a new list containing only the elements whose length does not exceed the given maximum length.

      Elements with length > maxLength are excluded. The original list is not modified.

      Creates a new LinkedListOfStrings by traversing this list in reverse (to preserve front-to-back order) and adding elements whose length is ≤ maxLength. Runs in O(n) time.

      Specified by:
      filterLargerThan in interface IListOfStrings
      Parameters:
      maxLength - the maximum allowed string length (inclusive)
      Returns:
      a new IListOfStrings with all oversized elements removed
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - if maxLength is negative

    • hasDuplicates

      public boolean hasDuplicates()
      Checks whether this list contains at least one duplicate element.

      Two elements are considered duplicates if they are equal by String.equals(Object).

      For each element, scans all subsequent elements to find a match. Runs in O(n²) time in the worst case.

      Specified by:
      hasDuplicates in interface IListOfStrings
      Returns:
      true if any element appears more than once; false otherwise

    • removeDuplicates

      public IListOfStrings removeDuplicates()
      Returns a new list with all duplicate elements removed, retaining only the first occurrence of each unique string.

      The original list is not modified. Relative order of first occurrences is preserved.

      Traverses the list once and keeps only the first occurrence of each unique string. Uses a helper LinkedListOfStrings as a "seen" set. Preserves original order of first occurrences. Runs in O(n²) time.

      Specified by:
      removeDuplicates in interface IListOfStrings
      Returns:
      a new IListOfStrings with duplicates removed
